<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE MAJOR LEAGUES; GIANTS' ROGERS HAS SURGERY 
FOR CLOT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 San Francisco Giant reliever Kevin Rogers was recovering Thursday from surgery 
on a clotted shoulder artery, a dangerous condition that has affected other 
hard-throwing pitchers and in 1980 ended the career of J.R. Richard. 
</P>
<P>
 On Wednesday, doctors at Stanford University Hospital tied off a blocked 
artery in Rogers' left shoulder, an operation that will keep him out of action 
for several weeks and could sidetrack his career. 
</P>
<P>
 The surgery came six days after tests determined that the coldness and 
numbness Rogers felt in his throwing arm and fingers were caused by a blood 
clot in a small artery in his shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
 Rogers, 25, is expected to recover in three weeks, but his return to baseball 
will depend on how quickly his circulation improves. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Florida Marlin reliever Jeremy Hernandez, who has been filling in for injured 
closer Bryan Harvey, has a bulging disk in his neck that will require 
season-ending surgery. 
</P>
<P>
 The Marlins called up former Angel Willie Fraser. 
</P>
