<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLUB REVIEW; BIG CROWD AT STIGMATA LOOKS LOCKED IN THE DAZE OF THE '80S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HEIDI SIEGMUND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The long line outside Stigmata may suggest that folks wish to partake in the 
club's activities, which continue until 4 a.m. Inside, however, nobody appears 
to be having much fun. The Friday night club at the Probe in Hollywood seems to 
be locked in a creepy warp, circa '85.Although the '80s -- shudder -- are 
already inching their way back into vogue, Stigmata reflects a period that 
surely no one willingly wants to recall. 
</P>
<P>
 Guys wear frowns and tights, gals wear Siouxsie & the Banshees 
makeup-by-numbers. Fights break out over requests to bum a cigarette by people 
who don't appear to be 18 -- the required age to get inside the cavernous, 
two-level club. Those who aren't dressed to depress appear just as exquisitely 
bored as their black-clad brethren. 
</P>
<P>
 The deejays' music, which focuses primarily on new wave and industrial, isn't 
inventive enough to breathe much life into the club, though a recent set's 
sandwiching of Revolting Cocks' industrial version of Rod Stewart's "Da Ya 
Think I'm Sexy?" between some prerequisite Nine Inch Nails and Siouxsie gave 
the scene a momentary shot in the arm. 
</P>
<P>
 * Stigmata, Fridays at the Probe, 836 N. Highland Ave., Hollywood, (213) 
462-7442, $8 cover with one-time $2 membership fee. HEIDI SIEGMUND 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Concert Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA060394-0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 047826 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
