<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: MOORPARK; POLICE STOREFRONT PLAN HITS A SNAG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city of Moorpark will delay for another two weeks a decision on whether to 
open a police storefront in a vacant city-owned building downtown, after an 
agreement with a private company to share the building and pay the rent was 
cast in doubt. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the plan, the police storefront would share space in the former bank 
building with an engineering company that performs building and safety 
inspections for the city. The company, Charles Abbott and Associates, would pay 
for repairs on the building in lieu of rent. 
</P>
<P>
 After the $30,000 to $40,000 in repairs were finished in two years or more, 
the company would begin paying rent to city. Abbott needs a larger office and 
had been looking for a downtown location. 
</P>
<P>
 But City Council members learned Wednesday that Abbott may rescind its offer 
to share with the police if the city follows through on a plan to perform its 
own building and safety inspections. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's no question that there is strong support for the police storefront," 
said councilman Pat Hunter, who first proposed the idea. "But this is dependent 
on Abbott and Associates renting the building, and if they're out of the 
picture we have to rethink how we can make this happen." 
</P>
<P>
 Hunter's proposal calls for using most of the building, on the corner of High 
Street and Moorpark Avenue, to house Abbott and Associates, and setting aside 
about 120 square feet for a police substation. 
</P>
<P>
 A police cadet or civilian would be assigned to the station about 20 hours per 
week at a cost of $15,000 to $20,000 per year. Moorpark is patrolled by a 
20-member force of sheriff's deputies that operates out of the East County 
sheriff's office in Thousand Oaks.  
</P>
<P>
 Hunter said the plan would help increase public safety in the town and help 
local businesses. 
</P>
<P>
 "A lot of this has to do with perceptions about safety," Hunter said. "If 
people see more police in the area, they are going to feel safer -- safer to go 
out at night, or walk downtown and go to the businesses down there." 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council will discuss the proposal again at a meeting at 7 p.m. 
Wednesday at City Hall, 799 Moorpark Ave. SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</TEXT>
