<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: POINT MUGU; INQUIRY CONTINUES IN EMERGENCY LANDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PEGGY Y. LEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Military officials on Thursday said they are still investigating why a 
helicopter that took off from Point Mugu Naval Air Weapons Station was forced 
to make an emergency landing near Lake Pyramid. 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't know what happened," said Cpl.Jeff Evans, spokesman for the Marine 
Corps Air Station El Toro, where the UH-1 Huey helicopter was based. "It's 
still under investigation." 
</P>
<P>
 A helicopter carrying six Marines from Camp Pendleton made a stop at Point 
Mugu and left about 6:05 p.m. Tuesday, Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
 About 7:30 p.m., the aircraft was forced to land two miles southwest of Lake 
Pyramid, Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
 None of the Marines were hurt during the landing, and the helicopter sustained 
minor damage, Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Marines were scouting the area to look for a place to establish a 
communications relay site, Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
 A military investigation in such cases typically lasts four to six weeks, 
officials said. PEGGY Y. LEE 
</P>
