<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COSTA MESA; FISH FRY, CARNIVAL WILL BEGIN TODAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLSON CUMMER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Organizers of the Lions Fish Fry and Carnival are expecting more than 20,000 
people to attend a parade Saturday, and hope to raise more than $140,000 for 
charity. 
</P>
<P>
 The 10 a.m. parade will be on Harbor Boulevard between Victoria and 19th 
streets, parade organizer Hugo Hunziker said.He said the parade is 
traditionally the highlight of the three-day event. 
</P>
<P>
 "The weather looks good, and that has a lot to do with it," Hunziker said 
Thursday. "I think it'll be great." 
</P>
<P>
 The Lions will donate money to the UC Irvine eye bank, to youth clubs, soup 
kitchens, senior citizens groups and other organizations, Hunziker said. 
</P>
<P>
 Fish dinners will be sold for $5 each. Carnival rides and the fish dinners 
will start today at 5:30 p.m. and run through Sunday. The fish fry, carnival, 
stage shows and a beauty contest will be held at Lions Park, at 18th Street and 
Anaheim Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
 Events are from 5:30 to 9 p.m. today; 10 a.m. to 9 p.m. Saturday; and noon to 
8 p.m. Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 An estimated 60,000 people are expected over the length of the fish fry and 
carnival. WILLSON CUMMER 
</P>
