<HEADLINE>
<P>
LEAST TERN RESERVE TAKES A SERIOUS TURN FOR THE WORSE; WILDLIFE: NESTING 
GROUNDS IN THE BOLSA CHICA WETLANDS HAVE BEEN PLAGUED BY FOX AND HAWK 
PREDATION. A BIOLOGIST FEARS THAT THE POPULATION WILL BE SO DEPLETED THAT THERE 
WILL BE NO CHICKS TO RETURN NEXT YEAR. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID HALDANE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A red fox and a sparrow hawk have raided more than two-thirds of the nests of 
least terns at the Bolsa Chica wetlands, jeopardizing the colony of the 
endangered species at the reserve. 
</P>
<P>
 The ecological reserve is home to about 10% of the state's population of the 
bird. 
</P>
<P>
 The problem began last month when a red fox attacked 60 of the bird colony's 
90 nests, wiping out about two-thirds of its eggs. Troy Kelly, a California 
Department of Fish and Game biologist, said it was the most devastating attack 
by a predator since the breeding area was established in the late 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
 In recent days, Kelly said, a marauding American kestrel -- commonly known as 
a sparrow hawk -- has carted off more than a dozen of the terns' surviving 
chicks, raising concerns about the colony's future. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's a potential of losing the entire nesting effort for this year at 
Bolsa Chica," Kelly said. If that happens, he said, the birds might never come 
back. "The situation is pretty critical," Kelly said. "I'm very concerned." 
</P>
<P>
 Fox attacks are not uncommon. A red fox preyed on the birds in Bolsa Chica two 
years ago, but the damage was not so extensive. 
</P>
<P>
 This year, the alarm was sounded early last month when a volunteer visiting a 
half-acre breeding island noticed the destroyed tern nests. 
</P>
<P>
 A small bird with a black cap and yellow bill, the California least tern 
numbers about 2,000 mating pairs statewide and is on state and federal 
endangered species lists. It generally spends the winter in South America. 
About mid-April, Kelly said, the birds migrate north to various California 
locations, including Bolsa Chica, where they nest in the sand and lay eggs that 
hatch in late May or early June. 
</P>
<P>
 Until 1978, the wetlands attracted an annual least tern population of only 
about 25 mating pairs. But a breeding island was built, complete with open 
stretches of sand and tile shelters for older chicks. Today, the area is 
visited annually by about 200 mating pairs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Kelly -- who oversees six wetlands areas in Southern California -- was at a 
meeting in Sacramento when he heard of the volunteer's discovery that a fox had 
raided nests. He rushed home, he said, and for three nights he slept in his car 
near the breeding grounds, armed with a spotlight and shotgun and hoping that 
the fox would return. Then, at an expense of about $5,000, the state hired a 
professional trapper who unsuccessfully stalked the animal for 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
 "He was probably just passing through," Kelly said of the fox. "He could 
return." 
</P>
<P>
 That would spell major trouble, the biologist said. No more funds are 
available to hire another trapper. And with his staff thinned by budget cuts, 
all he can do is patrol the area regularly with shotgun at hand, Kelly said. 
</P>
<P>
 It was during a patrol this week that the biologist encountered evidence of 
the second major threat to the area's least tern population: a foraging sparrow 
hawk preying on the tern's newly hatched chicks. Under normal circumstances, 
Kelly said, the birds could defend against such attacks by mobbing an intruder. 
With their numbers decreased, however, they are easily overcome. 
</P>
<P>
 "The hawk worries me," Kelly said. "If I don't do something about it quickly, 
he could do more damage than the fox." 
</P>
<P>
 The biologist said he plans to spend the next several days waiting for the 
predator with his shotgun. "It's a constant battle," he said. "We don't like 
shooting birds, but you have to weigh the various factors, and right now the 
least tern weighs more heavily than the hawk." 
</P>
</TEXT>
