<P>
 The race to acquire Famous Music Publishing from debt-heavy Viacom is about to 
heat up, with industry chatter saying the sale's point man, CAA's Michael 
Ovitz, is encountering some very copyright-hungry suitors. Insiders estimate 
that the company, which owns more than 100,000 copyrights, has profit of $5 
million to $7 million annually and could be sold for as much as $150 million to 
$200 million.Early handicapping is designating front-runner status to recent 
start-ups Sony Music Publishing and PolyGram Music Publishing, which are intent 
on building up their catalogues. * 
